1. Fork ODH/kserve to your personal account, then clone it:
$ git clone git@github.com:<your GH username>/kserve.git

2. add down, mid (odh) and upstream kserve as remote
$ git remote add <upstream remote name>  git@github.com:kserve/kserve.git
$ git remote add <odh remote name> git@github.com:opendatahub-io/kserve.git
$ git remote add <rhds remote name> git@github.com:red-hat-data-services/kserve.git

At the end you should have something like this
$ git remote -v
community	git@github.com:kserve/kserve.git (fetch)
community	git@github.com:kserve/kserve.git (push)`
downstream	git@github.com:red-hat-data-services/kserve.git (fetch)
downstream	git@github.com:red-hat-data-services/kserve.git (push)
origin	git@github.com:spolti/kserve.git (fetch)
origin	git@github.com:spolti/kserve.git (push)
upstream	git@github.com:opendatahub-io/kserve.git (fetch)
upstream	git@github.com:opendatahub-io/kserve.git (push)


3. checkout kserve upstream (following my remote names as example), create the community master branch and start a new branch for the changes from there:
$ git fetch community
$ git checkout community/master # change the current branch to upstream/community master
$ git checkout -b community-master # create the community-master branch